config.text: Great Salt Lake Brine Chemistry Database

The salinity level of Great Salt Lake (GSL) is quite dynamic due to natural lake level fluctuations and man-made barriers within the lake. At a number of sites throughout the lake, the UGS takes samples at various depths through the water column, measures those samples for density, and analyzes them for chemistry. This sampling program has largely been funded by the Utah Division of Forestry, Fire and State Lands.

Chart Data

Use the depth and chemical filters below to view the data of interest.

config.text:
This heatmap shows monthly chemical conditions of active sampling sites at the Great Salt Lake. Use the slider or play button to view monthly changes.


Interpretation guide:

  1. Heatmap shows interpolated density (darker blue = higher g/cm) or salinity (darker green = higher g/L).
  2. Circles are sampling stations; color matches legend if data exists.
  3. Observe potential correlations between temperature (Avg Temp) and density or salinity patterns.
  4. Data is interpolated between stations using inverse distance weighting.

config.text: Great Salt Lake Brine Chemistry Database

This page serves as a hub for technical reports, research studies, and other documents related to Great Salt Lake from state agencies, research and preservation organizations, and other stakeholders. A primary purpose of the archive is to preserve Great Salt Lake reports and documents that are unpublished. The available material includes information from various disciplines (e.g., hydrology, ecology, and chemistry) to serve as a resource for informed decision-making, sustainable management practices, and further research. If you are aware of Great Salt Lake documents in need of preservation, please contact Andrew Rupke (andrewrupke@utah.gov).
